{
  "texts": [
    "Reinforcement Learning uses the formal framework of the Markov Decision Process (MDP) to define the interaction between a learning agent and its environment regarding states, actions, and rewards.",
    "An MDP is defined by a tuple (S, A, P, R, γ), so that: S represents a set of states; A is a set of actions A = {a 1, a 2,.",
    ", a n }; P(s | s, a) is the probability of transiting from state s to s (s, s ∈ S) by taking action a ∈ A; R is a reward function mapping each state-action pair to a reward in R; and γ ∈ [0, 1] is a discount factor.",
    "A policy π represents the agent's behavior, and the value π(a | s) represents the probability of taking action a in state s. At each time step t, the agent observes a state s t ∈ S and chooses an action a t ∈ A that determines the reward r t = R(s t, a t) and the next state s t+1 ∼ P(• | s t, a t), causing a transition of states T (s, a, s).",
    "A discounted sum of future rewards is called return R t = ∞ t =t γ t -t r t."
  ]
}